This group of borrowers consists of four residents of Siem Reap Province, led by S., 33, a responsible neighbor and mother of three children, all of whom are single and under her care.  Married to Theoun, 33, a local construction worker, S. has been a cleaning worker in a private company for more than a year.  In order to end her reliance on motor taxi transportation to her place of work, she is requesting a loan that, coupled with her savings, will allow for the purchase of a motorbike. <p>

The other three members of this group loan are: 

C., 42, who is requesting a loan to buy more rice for her store; 

T., 45, who raises piglets and is seeking to buy a motorbike for her and her family;

P., 46, who is looking for a loan to buy more piglets for her business.

This group of borrowers consists of five members, all residents of Siem Reap Province, led by Tuk M., 40, a responsible neighbor and the mother of two children, both of whom are single and under her care. Married to Soth, 30, a motor taxi driver, Tuk sells a variety of sweets made from soybean, pumpkin, gelatin, etc., to the people in the commune. Because of the family home’s confined nature, she is requesting a loan to renovate the house and build another kitchen room, the addition of which will facilitate her business operation. <p>

The other four members are: 

Mrs. T., 29, a laborer seeking a loan to buy poles for her house; 

Mrs. Phallaa 32, a laborer requesting a loan to renovate her house;

Mrs. C., 35, a fresh water shell seller looking for a loan to buy poles for her house;

Mrs. S., 30, a laborer requesting a loan to renovate her house.
